<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="102">
IV. - 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2365" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Atopomyrmex</taxonomicName>
et genres voisins.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="102">
M. Ernest Andre a fon le le genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2365" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Atopomyrmex</taxonomicName>
sur l'ouvriere d'une seule espece: 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25933" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex mocquerysi AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex mocquerysi Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mocquerysi">A. mocquerysi</taxonomicName>
. Depuis lors, j'ai decrit la femelle d'une espece voisine (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25932" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex cryptoceroides Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex cryptoceroides Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cryptoceroides">A. cryptoceroides</taxonomicName>
) et Mayr en decrivit l'ouvriere sous le nom de / 1. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:134277" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex deplanatus Mayr" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex deplanatus Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="deplanatus">deplanatus</taxonomicName>
. En 1895, ayant a determiner les fourmis recoltees par M. Alluaud a Madagascar, je crus pouvoir rapporter une espece au genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2365" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Atopomyrmex</taxonomicName>
; elle avait de tres particulier deux epines au petiole, comme VA. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25933" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex mocquerysi AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex mocquerysi Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mocquerysi">mocquerysi</taxonomicName>
. Dans ces derniers temps, les especes attribuees au genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2365" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Atopomyrmex</taxonomicName>
se sont accrues notablement et je n'ai pas peu, pour ma part, contribue a rendre ce genre heterogene. J'ai fait connaitre, en 1900, une espece de Madagascar (
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:144856" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex foreli Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex foreli Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foreli">A. foreli</taxonomicName>
), qui se rapproche de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:144854" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex alluaudi Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex alluaudi Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alluaudi">A. alluaudi</taxonomicName>
; en meme temps, j'ai decrit et figure le male singulier que j'ai suppose lui appartenir. M. Forel m'ecrit qu'il a dans sa collection les males de deux especes voisines, ce qui confirme ma supposition.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="102">
Recemment, M. Santschi, a porte la cognee dans ce buisson epineux: il en a separe le genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2515" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dilobocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilobocondyla Santschi" lsidName-HNS="Dilobocondyla Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilobocondyla</taxonomicName>
, comprenante, sele-bensis Emery, et une nouvelle espece 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:28595" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dilobocondyla" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilobocondyla fouqueti Santschi" lsidName-HNS="Dilobocondyla fouqueti Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fouqueti">D. fouqueti</taxonomicName>
(1). Il m'ecrit encore tout dernierement, que le type de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:230742" genus="Mesomyrma" lsidName-HNS="Mesomyrma cataulacoidea" pageNumber="102" rank="species" species="cataulacoidea">Mesomyrma cataulacoidea</taxonomicName>
Stitz, qu'il a eu l'occasion de voir, est un vrai 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2515" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Dilobocondyla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Dilobocondyla Santschi" lsidName-HNS="Dilobocondyla Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Dilobocondyla</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="102">
Maintenant, je pense que des males, comme celui d' 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:144856" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex foreli Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex foreli Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foreli">A. foreli</taxonomicName>
, ne peuvent etre compris dans un seul genre avec des femelles comme celles d' 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25932" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex cryptoceroides Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex cryptoceroides Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cryptoceroides">A. cryptoceroides</taxonomicName>
et 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:230743" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex ceylonensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceylonensis">ceylonensis</taxonomicName>
, et cela a cause de leurs ailes qui sont radicalement differentes dans leur nervulation (confronter ma figure du [[ male ]] de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:144856" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex foreli Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex foreli Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="foreli">A. foreli</taxonomicName>
(Bull. Soc. Ent. Ital., vol. 31, p. 275, 1900) avec celle de la [[ queen ]] de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:230743" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex ceylonensis" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceylonensis">A. ceylonensis</taxonomicName>
(Deutsche Ent. Zeitschr., 1901, p. 114); l'aile de 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:25932" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex cryptoceroides Emery" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex cryptoceroides Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cryptoceroides">A. cryptoceroides</taxonomicName>
[[ queen ]] est a peu pres semblable).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="102">
Selon mon opinion, il faudrait partager en trois le genre 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2365" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atopomyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Atopomyrmex AndrÃ©" lsidName-HNS="Atopomyrmex Andre" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Atopomyrmex</taxonomicName>
, etant donnees les especes qui y sont placees actuellement:
</paragraph>
